Self-Driving Car Engineer Nanodegree¶

Project: Finding Lane Lines on the Road¶

The aim of the project is to identify lane lines on the road. The code needs to process the video frames captured by a mounted camera on the Car, and identify the lane lines and overlay them on the video.

Modified Helper Functions¶

Below are some helper functions to help get you started. They should look familiar from the lesson!

def grayscale(img):
    """Applies the Grayscale transform
    This will return an image with only one color channel
    but NOTE: to see the returned image as grayscale
    (assuming your grayscaled image is called 'gray')
    you should call plt.imshow(gray, cmap='gray')"""
    return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)
    # Or use BGR2GRAY if you read an image with cv2.imread()
    # return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    
def hsvscale(img):
    """Applies the hsv transform"""
    return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2HSV)
    
def canny(img, low_threshold, high_threshold):
    """Applies the Canny transform"""
    return cv2.Canny(img, low_threshold, high_threshold)

def gaussian_blur(img, kernel_size):
    """Applies a Gaussian Noise kernel"""
    return cv2.GaussianBlur(img, (kernel_size, kernel_size), 0)

def region_of_interest(img, vertices,region_include = True):
    """
    Applies an image mask.
    
    Only keeps the region of the image defined by the polygon
    formed from `vertices`. The rest of the image is set to black.
    """
    #defining a blank mask to start with
    mask = np.zeros_like(img)   
    
    #defining a 3 channel or 1 channel color to fill the mask with depending on the input image
    if len(img.shape) > 2:
        channel_count = img.shape[2]  # i.e. 3 or 4 depending on your image
        ignore_mask_color = (255,) * channel_count
    else:
        ignore_mask_color = 255
    
    #filling pixels inside the polygon defined by "vertices" with the fill color    
    cv2.fillPoly(mask, vertices, ignore_mask_color)
    
    #for region exclude invert the mask
    if region_include == False:
        mask = 255*np.ones_like(img) - mask

    #returning the image only where mask pixels are nonzero
    masked_image = cv2.bitwise_and(img, mask)
    return masked_image

def draw_lines(img, lines, color=[255], thickness=1):
    """
    This function draws `lines` with `color` and `thickness`.    
    Lines are drawn on the image inplace (mutates the image).
    If you want to make the lines semi-transparent, think about combining
    this function with the weighted_img() function below
    
    Implementing hard-coded rules on slope is slightly tricky as these
    are not robust and not a clean approach
    I have implemented here a very simple rule that the angle should be 
    greater than 30 degree
    """
    for line in lines:
        for x1,y1,x2,y2 in line:
            slope=((y2-y1)*(x2-x1)/((abs(x2-x1)+1)*(abs(x2-x1)+1)))
            if(abs(slope)>0.0001):
                cv2.line(img, (int(x1),int(y1)), (int(x2), int(y2)), color, thickness)

def hough_lines(img, rho, theta, threshold, min_line_len, max_line_gap):
    """
    `img` should be the output of a Canny transform.
        
    Returns hough lines
    """
    lines = cv2.HoughLinesP(img, rho, theta, threshold, np.array([]), minLineLength=min_line_len, maxLineGap=max_line_gap)
    line_img = np.zeros((img.shape[0], img.shape[1], 1), dtype=np.uint8)
    draw_lines(line_img, lines)
    return lines,line_img    

# Python 3 has support for cool math symbols.

def weighted_img(img, initial_img, =0.8, =1, =0.):
    """
    `img` is the output of the hough_lines(), An image with lines drawn on it.
    Should be a blank image (all black) with lines drawn on it.
    
    `initial_img` should be the image before any processing.
    
    The result image is computed as follows:
    
    initial_img *  + img *  + 
    NOTE: initial_img and img must be the same shape!
    """
    return cv2.addWeighted(initial_img, , img, , )


def ransac_polyfit(x, y, order=3, n=20, k=100, t=5, d=100, f=0.8):
    """
    This function implements a ransac algorithm for poly fit.
    A persistent problem with line fitting algorithm is noise
    makes good fits impossible. RANSAC randomly samples and fits
    curves to find the best fit
    https://gist.github.com/geohot/9743ad59598daf61155bf0d43a10838c

    # Thanks https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_sample_consensus

    # n  minimum number of data points required to fit the model
    # k  maximum number of iterations allowed in the algorithm
    # t  threshold value to determine when a data point fits a model
    # d  number of close data points required to assert that a model fits well to data
    # f  fraction of close data points required
    """

    besterr = np.inf
    bestfit = np.array([])
    if(n/2 > len(x)):
        return bestfit
    for kk in range(k):
        maybeinliers = np.random.randint(len(x), size=n)
        maybeinliers = np.asarray(maybeinliers,np.int32)
        maybemodel = np.polyfit(x[maybeinliers], y[maybeinliers], order)
        alsoinliers = np.abs(np.polyval(maybemodel, x)-y) < t
        if sum(alsoinliers) > d and sum(alsoinliers) > len(x)*f:
            bettermodel = np.polyfit(x[alsoinliers], y[alsoinliers], order)
            thiserr = np.sum(np.abs(np.polyval(bettermodel, x[alsoinliers])-y[alsoinliers]))
            if thiserr < besterr:
                bestfit = bettermodel
                besterr = thiserr
    return bestfit

def apply_mask(imgin):
    """
    This function applies the inclusion exclusion mask to removes the areas which
    are outside of region of interest so the noise effect is minimimum"""
    mask_idx = np.array([[(430/960.0,320/540.0),(540/960.0,320/540.0),(920/960.0,538/540.0),(100/960.0,538/540.0)]],dtype=np.float32)
    mask_idx = np.multiply(np.array([imgin.shape[1],imgin.shape[0]]),mask_idx)
    
    #Removes all noise outside center region
    imgout = region_of_interest(imgin,np.asarray(mask_idx,dtype=np.int32))

    mask_idx = np.array([[(430/960.0,400/540.0),(540/960.0,400/540.0),(760/960.0,538/540.0),(300/960.0,538/540.0)]],dtype=np.float32)
    mask_idx = np.multiply(np.array([imgin.shape[1],imgin.shape[0]]),mask_idx)
    
    #Removes all noise under center region
    imgout = region_of_interest(imgout,np.asarray(mask_idx,dtype=np.int32),False)
    
    return imgout
    
def find_white_markings(imgin):
    """
    This function finds the white marking on the road. The same function
    can work for yellow lines but results are not very reliable and get 
    affected by shadows and high illumination
    """
    img_channel =  np.squeeze(np.maximum(np.maximum(imgin[:,:,1],imgin[:,:,2]),imgin[:,:,0]))
    img_channel_smoothened = gaussian_blur(img_channel,9)
    img_canny = canny(img_channel_smoothened,60,80)    
    
    #apply inclusion/exclusion mask
    img_binarized = apply_mask(img_canny)

    #get hough lines as 1-0
    lines,img_hgh_lines = hough_lines(img_binarized, 1, 1*np.pi/180,4,5, 10)

    #fill the holes made by drawing the hough lines to create uniform strips
    kernel = np.ones((7,7),np.uint8)
    img_binarized = cv2.morphologyEx(np.squeeze(img_hgh_lines), cv2.MORPH_CLOSE, kernel)

#    return img_normalize
    return img_binarized

def find_yellow_markings(imgin):
    """
    This function finds the yellow marking on the road. It uses HSV 
    transform to generate the hue,saturation,value component of the image
    Then it uses cv2.inRange to find the relevant yellow pixels in the image
    """
    img_hsv = hsvscale(imgin)
    
    #bounds for yellow color
    lower_yellow = np.array([15,65,65])
    upper_yellow = np.array([35,255,255])

    # Threshold the HSV image to get only yellow colors
    yellow_region = cv2.inRange(img_hsv, lower_yellow, upper_yellow)
     
    #apply inclusion/exclusion mask
    mask = apply_mask(yellow_region)
    #fill the holes to create uniform strips
    kernel = np.ones((5,5),np.uint8)
    mask_close = cv2.morphologyEx(mask, cv2.MORPH_CLOSE, kernel)
    
    return mask_close

def get_skel(imgin):
    """
    This function implements the morphological operaiton of obtaining
    skeleton of the binary image. This function is to good center 
    relevant points so line fitting is easier
    """
    element = np.ones((3,3),np.uint8)#v2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_CROSS,(3,3))
    done = False
    img = imgin
    size = np.size(img)
    skel = np.zeros(img.shape,np.uint8)

    while( not done):
        eroded = cv2.erode(img,element)
        temp = cv2.dilate(eroded,element)
        temp = cv2.subtract(img,temp)
        skel = cv2.bitwise_or(skel,temp)
        img = eroded.copy()

        zeros = size - cv2.countNonZero(img)
        if zeros==size:
            done = True

    return skel

def draw_poly_fit(imgin,poly_fitted):
    """
    This functions draws the fitted lines on the maskimg.
    It evaluates the polynomial points and then check for
    their ranges and then draw.
    """
    xc = np.array(range(imgin.shape[0]))
    aaa = int(320.0 *imgin.shape[0]/540.0);
    
    xc = np.array(range(imgin.shape[0]-aaa))
    xc = xc+aaa;
    
    #load polynomial
    p = np.poly1d(poly_fitted)
    
    #evaluate
    yc = p(xc)
    
    yc = np.asarray(yc,dtype=np.int32)

    #check bounds
    yc1 = yc[yc>=0]
    yc2 = yc1[yc1<imgin.shape[1]]
    xc1 = xc[yc>=0]
    xc2 = xc1[yc1<imgin.shape[1]]

    mask_img = np.array(imgin)*0;
    for ixx in np.array(range(yc2.shape[0]-1)):
        cv2.line(mask_img, (yc2[ixx],xc2[ixx]), (yc2[ixx+1], xc2[ixx+1]), [255,0,0], 5)

    return mask_img


def find_lane_line(imgin,img_binarized,prev_frame_fit,isleft = True):
    """
    This function finds the points in the mask images
    and tries to fit a first order polynomial(line) and on
    failing for a good fit tries to find the second order
    polynomial and if unsuccessful default to prev frame
    """
    
    a,b = np.nonzero(img_binarized);
    yindx = int(img_binarized.shape[1]*0.52);

    if isleft == False:
        a = a[b>yindx]
        b = b[b>yindx]
    else:
        a = a[b<=yindx]
        b = b[b<=yindx]
        
    # try first order polynomial if it fit
    fit_poly = ransac_polyfit(a, b, order=1, n=20, k=300, t=8, d=60, f=0.6)
    if len(fit_poly) == 0:
        # try second order_polynomial
        fit_poly = ransac_polyfit(a, b, order=2, n=20, k=500, t=15, d=60, f=0.7)
    #if fails to find in current frame, use from nearby frames
    if(len(fit_poly) == 0):
        fit_poly = prev_frame_fit;

    drawn_lane_line = draw_poly_fit(imgin,fit_poly)

    return drawn_lane_line,fit_poly

Building the pipeline using functions above¶

In [6]:
"""
    This function has the entire pipeline for the project.
    It first find the lane markings using the edge/color.
    Then it find those as skeltons and fits polynomial functions
    using RANSAC. It then draws those polynomials on the image
"""
def pipeline(imgin):
  
    #find the yellow and white marking
    img_white = find_white_markings(imgin)
    img_yellow = find_yellow_markings(imgin)

    #return(np.concatenate((img_white[:,:,np.newaxis],img_white[:,:,np.newaxis],img_white[:,:,np.newaxis]),axis=2))

    #add up the results
    lanes_binarized = np.maximum(img_yellow,img_white)
    
    #create a buffer in between lines
    yindx = int(lanes_binarized.shape[1]*0.52);
    lanes_binarized[:,yindx-20:yindx+2] = 0;
    
    #generate single width line
    skel_lanes_binarized = get_skel(lanes_binarized)

    #fetch temporal poly_fit_coeff and find lanes by polyfitting
    global prev_l
    global prev_r
    left_lane_mask,prev_l = find_lane_line(imgin,skel_lanes_binarized,prev_l,isleft = True)
    right_lane_mask,prev_r = find_lane_line(imgin,skel_lanes_binarized,prev_r,isleft = False)

    lanes_mask = np.maximum(left_lane_mask,right_lane_mask)

    #Adding the lane mask to original images
    imgout = (weighted_img(lanes_mask,imgin))

    #return(np.concatenate((img_white[:,:,np.newaxis],img_white[:,:,np.newaxis],img_white[:,:,np.newaxis]),axis=2))
    return imgout

Improve the draw_lines() function¶

At this point, if you were successful with making the pipeline and tuning parameters, you probably have the Hough line segments drawn onto the road, but what about identifying the full extent of the lane and marking it clearly as in the example video (P1_example.mp4)? Think about defining a line to run the full length of the visible lane based on the line segments you identified with the Hough Transform. As mentioned previously, try to average and/or extrapolate the line segments you've detected to map out the full extent of the lane lines. You can see an example of the result you're going for in the video "P1_example.mp4".

Go back and modify your draw_lines function accordingly and try re-running your pipeline. The new output should draw a single, solid line over the left lane line and a single, solid line over the right lane line. The lines should start from the bottom of the image and extend out to the top of the region of interest.
